### Postpartum obsessive‐compulsive disorder {#dmcn13897-sec-0011}

Postpartum obsessive compulsive disorder (PPOCD) is a common disorder that affects up to 10% of women who give birth. It is characterized by intrusive thoughts about harming or losing the baby, and by repetitive behaviors (e. g., checking or washing the baby, checking the baby\'s diaper, or checking the baby for signs of illness). The disorder is often associated with a history of depression and/or anxiety, and is often comorbid with other mood/ anxiety disorders. The disorder is also associated with a high risk of suicide.

### Diagnostic criteria {#dMCN13897s1-0003}

The diagnostic criteria for PPOCD are based on the DSM‐IV‐TR criteria for OCD, and are summarized in Table [1](#dmc13897t1){ref-type="table"}.

### What to know about vascular access\n\

Vascular access is the conduit through which blood is exchanged between the body and the vascular system. It is the most common site for vascular access in the United States, accounting for approximately 40% of all vascular access sites. The most common vascular access sites are the femoral, axillary, and brachial arteries. The brachial artery is the most commonly used site for vascular procedures, accounting for about 80% of all brachial access sites.

Vasculature is the largest organ in the body, and the largest organ that is not a blood vessel. The vascular system is made up of arteries, veins, and capillaries. The arteries supply blood to the heart, lungs, and other organs. The veins drain blood from the body. The capillaries are the smallest blood vessels in the body. They are the only blood vessels that do not have a lumen.

The vascular system is divided into three main parts: the arterial system, the venous system, and the lymphatic system. The arterial system is the largest part of the vascular system, and it is the most important part of the system. The arteries are the arteries that supply blood to all the organs in the body and are the arteries of the body.

This procedure is used to correct vaginal prolapse in women who are not candidates for a hysteretomy.

A TVR procedure is usually performed in a gynecology office.
